What's upside-down is declaring what other people may or may not demand,
expect, etc. There are lots of people who say absolutely you have no right
to own firearms, or to engage in &quot;hate speech,&quot; and so on. Now we have
somebody who says you have no right to a job, or a place to live, or health
care. In other words, if you have a string of bad luck, bub, that's too bad.
You die. Maybe we really wouldn't let you die, but we're within our &quot;rights&quot;
to let you croak. It's a matter of attitude, and underlying that whole list
is something that I see as a bad attitude.

You may object because you think some people are working from the wrong list
of rights. I object because some people think they can tell me what rights I
can demand.

There is no magical or God-given list of &quot;rights.&quot; Rights are what people
decide they are, through the political process. You can argue legitimately
what those rights should be. You cannot argue legitimately that someone
can't demand a right. If they get political agreement about what constitutes
a right (the right for women to vote, for example, or the right to be
treated equally regardless of one's race -- both &quot;rights&quot; that came along
many, many years after the Bill of Rights), then that's the way it goes.

Again, that list strikes a chord with most of us, and, as a social
commentary in the form of a joke (which it appears to be), it's funny and
there's nothing wrong with it. But taking it seriously, or posturing behind
it, requires a certain dystopic attitude and a bit of jingoism. What do you
mean, &quot;this is an English speaking country...learn it or go back where you
came from&quot;? Why? If somebody can hold a job and even thrive without English,
as many thousands of people do in Miami, then what the hell business of
YOURS is it what language they speak?

That's all I have to say about it. I'll laugh along with it, but it's
nothing more than a joke.

--
Ed Huntress
