I'll let you have the last word on this, Doug, after one last response.

If you read carefully you'll see that the ENTIRE POINT of the piece was not
that there are not God-given rights, but that there are no things to which
one is entitled. I don't know what the author thinks about the source of
rights, God, magic, or otherwise, because he doesn't say, but it doesn't
matter.

Without arguing about what rights are or not (it's a historical question
about where those principles come from, and you won't find the kind of
consistency among the Framers that some people claim), it's fair to say that
the most universal idea of rights today is closer to the UN's Universal
Declaration of Human Rights than it is to the US Bill of Rights. For
example, here's what Ronald Reagan had to say about the UDHR:

&quot;For people of good will around the world, that document is more than just
words: It's a global testament of humanity, a standard by which any humble
person on Earth can stand in judgment of any government on Earth.&quot;

Assuming that Reagan actually read it, you might be surprised to know what
it was that he praised as this standard of judgment for governments: Article
23: Everyone has the right to work, to free choice of employment, to just
and favourable conditions of work and to protection against
unemployment...Everyone who works has the right to just and favourable
remuneration ensuring for himself and his family an existence worthy of
human dignity, and supplemented, if necessary, by other means of social
protection. Article 25: Everyone has the right to a standard of living
adequate for the health and well-being of himself and of his family,
including food, clothing, housing and medical care and necessary social
services, and the right to security in the event of unemployment, sickness,
disability, widowhood, old age or other lack of livelihood in circumstances
beyond his control. Article 26: Everyone has the right to education.
Education shall be free, at least in the elementary and fundamental stages.

That's good ol' conservative Ronnie Reagan's idea of what government is
responsible for. Most people in the world would agree with him. They,
probably including most Americans, woud say that a government that can't be
construed to provide these things isn't worth the powder to blow it to hell.

Obviously, this is not your average libertarian's idea of &quot;rights,&quot; but your
average libertarian would go screaming into the sunset if he actually got
what it is he thinks he wants. He's certainly never experienced it because
we've lived for generations with a much more extensive idea of what it takes
to make a civil society. It's easy to prescribe extreme self-reliance when
you know you have a safety net under you, that you can always go to the
emergency room if things get rough.

And that's the basic problem with the list of &quot;NON rights&quot; that we're
talking about here. His attitude is one of incivility. In other words, he's
a selfish prick who's pumped up with self-righteousness. That wouldn't even
be too bad if he didn't give himself away with the comments about English.
That's a subject you have to think about carefully to avoid being foolish on
one hand or to be a jingoistic xenophobe on the other. He doesn't pass the
test. It's none of his damned business what language someone else speaks.
Switzerland gets along fine with three official and four national languages.
To say you have to speak mine, or get out, regardless of whether you're
self-sufficient and successful (like thousands of people in Miami, to give
just one example) is nothing like a libertarian, or a conservative
principle. It's just mean-spirited self-congratulation and dismissiveness
toward anyone who isn't like you. Which, of course, is what that whole &quot;Bill
on NON-rights&quot; is all about.

I'm done. It's all yours.

--
Ed Huntress
